< review>
Staff is friendly and very tentative.The Equipment is clean. Its not too crowded and parking is not a problem. There are lots of machines to choose from and the indoor pool stays warm for the kiddos. Its just a nice environment all the way around and the people there are not rude. I give this place 5 stars. I got signed up there by a rep by the name of Monica and she took the time to show me around and explain what memberships they had. I of course got the membership thats gets me in all the in shapes so yes i would definitely recommend the In-Shape located in Quail Lakes. Oh I forgot to mention they have plugins to charge your phone and that's a plus. I can't have my phone dying while working out.</review>

<userid>108731684830185365850</userid><Name>Chieh-Ting Chuang<//Name><date>1604985055718<//date>< Rate>
5<//Rate>
<review>I lived here for almost 3 years during my studies at UCLA. It was a great experience and super supportive of my financial condition. My favorite part of the co-op is to wake up with a hot breakfast and end a tiring school day with a good dinner. No matter how busy I am with my school work, I never have to worry about feeding myself. The variety of food is also good, you are expecting different food every day. Some of them are amazingly delicious.
While working for 4 hours a week seems a lot, it is not that bad. I worked as a kitchen chief for a while and it did cultivate my managing and communication skills with people.
People are also really nice. I came here as a non-native speaker and make lots of friends and at the same time build up my language skills. Whenever I need something urgent (such as batteries or light bulbs), there are always people that help me out.

In conclusion, this is a great place if you are a more outgoing person that can give up your privacy a bit. I do love this place and I like the communal living atmosphere a lot. However, if you think privacy is an important issue this place might not be a good place for you.

The photos are from several different rooms I've lived in for the years and the omelet for brunch every weekend :)< /review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM-OrUI98Z1JOWaWPvO5c0t1JFKatD8IVvwYEsa=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOaGKBJVXxIpQtZuHauwJyyTkwEg31lLWUTRFK8=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOCd9zw_fGNLCuSrILfwLsQM5lKmIl3cgsum1T4=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN1WKbCmW0cpygKjDtmDgEUErPWCIBDYXkZWL3s=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>< Resp>

<Review>I would highly recommend living here if you're interested in cooperative living. Very unique to live in a place that you partly own democratically. <date>1614364436018</date><userid>115206679154952415970</userid>< Text>
I love this place so much. Elsewhere in LA, it is like pulling teeth to make friends and be part of a community, especially during the pandemic times. Here, not only did I find myself in an established mini-world with a rich history and culture, but I was also able to take advantage of the low rent and an amazing meal plan. Doing the chore shifts becomes second nature after a while, and is a great opportunity to connect with more people in this little bubble. The co-op really inspired me to get out of my shell and feel accepted. It's a great place for students of all ages!</Text>

<Text>I've been living at UCHA for a quarter now, and I love it. I've gotten to meet a ton of cool people even during Covid because we work together on chore shifts and stuff. It's really cool to be part of a cooperative - it feels like we're all in this together. One of the best things about UCHA is that it's one of if not the, cheapest housing options in Westwood and this is partly because of the chore shifts that everyone is required to do. Again though, this aspect of the co-op highlights one of the other incredible things about it, that you get to meet a large range of people who you will live and work with throughout your time at the co-op. If you are looking for a cheap housing option that comes with meals (19 a week), a community, and ways to engage, then this is the place for you!<//Text><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOEScX1rXHyh940Qn1Sb-Yxj8H5QvaUDaShH6PM=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics>< Resp>

< review>
Living here is awesome! It is so close to UCLA and it really nice coming back to food cooked for you everyday. The rent is really cheap, my room came fully furnished with a brand new bed, dresser and desk. The entire place has been going through building renovations and my room was really nice with a beautiful view overlooking UCLA, Los Angeles & Santa Monica. The staff is really nice and supportive of my studies. I have met so many kids from around the world here. Every week we have to contribute 4 hours, I did mine in the kitchen. It was really fun learning to cook dishes and the chefs help you. The negative reviews are misleading. It's really simple and straightforward cheap living. If you do your 4 hours a week and keep your area/ room clean then its a great place. If you are lazy and don't then they put a fine on your account. The staff is just doing their job making sure everything is clean and nice. I highly recommend checking this place out if you are on a budget. I also met students that went to Cal States and Santa Monica College.<//review>

< Text>
Lived here for about a year. Awesome place and a great community! It's probably the best place in Westwood if you're not looking to pay an arm and a leg. You sign up on a quarterly basis which is amazing if you're looking to go abroad a quarter (you won't have to deal with finding a subletter, etc.) You get 19 meals per week but you're expected to do your job/chore 4 hours a week. The job is not bad and for what you get (19 meals/living in a fun community/parties/patio area/a little store in the co-op/cheap rent); it's a fantastic arrangement. The co-op also has a rich history (one of the first desegregated student housing communities in the nation/it offered refuge for Japanese-American students that faced discrimination during World War II) Also, it's nonprofit so I really don't think it would be possible to get a better deal. It's fun. It's weird. It's the co-op.</Text>

< user_id>
105534444647101605675< /user_id>
<Review>I was planning to live here for one quarter or two; I ended up staying for four years, and still contribute my time to this organization even after moving out. This student housing is perfect for international students and UCLA students who do not want to get screwed by the high college living cost, especially in Westwood( it provides Food, Utilities & more). Members get to meet lifelong friends & colleagues from all around the globe and they contribute their time to make this place better. This organization definitely gets better over the years. A lot of the bad reviews are from student who lived here a decade ago. I believe that my opinion is not an exception, because I have met many members along the way that shares the same opinion as mine.
If you are thinking of living here; be aware that this is more of a dorm and not apartments, you are living on the Frat Row (there will be noise on party nights, but some Coop buildings are quieter than others), don't be picky with food, be social (if you are more mature than the average college student, it might be hard to fit in and get along with people), you are responsible for doing your chores.
Unfortunately, the people who complains about this organization usually are members who are picky about food, people/culture, living style, & get into trouble because they do not pay rent on time, nor do their chores, etc. Members are paying for what they are getting, I don't know why people are expecting some Luxury Apartments when they are paying this cheap rent!
Overall, I am extremely grateful for this amazing & unique housing organization.</Review>< Rate>
5</Rate>

0x80c2957ee2d29c21:0xa3755ef9d5f9ca23< /gmapID>
< resp>
{'time': 1522683940675, 'text': "Jeremy, we are so glad that your daughter found a kitten.  Pets enrich the lives of people and her getting to grow up care for an animal is wonderful.  We are not exactly sure when you came into Operation Adopt since this review was just written (and we haven't had kittens in quite a while), but nonetheless we are hoping that giving you the reason why we don't allow everyone coming in to hold kittens (or puppies) helps you understand.  We don't allow people to hold them without an application on file for a few reasons.  First, everyone coming in would want to hold them and given that we are a pet adoption center with a large number of animals instead of just a pet supply store like the place you mentioned, we give first priority to people with applications on file because going through the process shows us that people are serious about adopting - not just holding animals - which helps our staff and volunteers know where to focus (because it they had to let everyone hold animals, they wouldn't have time to dedicate tho their primary role of caring for the animals).  Secondly, and most importantly, diseases spread by touch, and young animals are extremely vulnerable.  Let's say for instance someone was looking for a puppy or kitten and had been visiting local shelters and holding multiple animals - and one of those animals had a disease.  Diseases in shelters are sometimes fatal and many are contagious not only to other animals, but humans as well.  So, by allowing anyone coming in to touch or hold animals, we are putting our animals and people at risk.  This is another reason we require people to sanitize their hands prior to interacting with our animals.  We are sure the kitten you adopted is healthy and disease free, but hope you understand that we take a lot of precautions to care for our animals and humans coming into contact with them."}<//resp>

{'time': 1516741560397, 'text': 'Shelters use many different methods to adopt animals such as first come, lottery drawing and bidding. When we get to a kill shelter, very rarely are any people there wanting to adopt the same animal. Thatâ€™s hardly ever happened.  If it does, and if that particular shelter has an "open and fair" bidding process as set forth in their municipal code, and if our trained staff has already spent hours of time and travel assessing an animal to become part of our adoption process, then we move forward to adopt the animal. That feels both fair and just to us; more importantly, it is in line with our mission to save as many animals as possible from kill shelters and find them the best forever homes while in the process freeing up space to allow more at risk animals additional time to find homes.'}<//Resp>

< Review>
The people at this place are exceptionally nice and seem to take very good care of the pets. Iâ€™m giving  one star because their model doesnâ€™t serve any purpose other than satisfying some pretty troubling elitist attitudes regarding shelters and removing â€œhighly adoptableâ€ dogs from qualified middle and low income adopters. Hear me out.

Based on my visit to their store and information on their website, TAPS selects dogs that have a high probability of adoption, i.e., very cute, young dogs and puppies. I didnâ€™t see a single pit bull though itâ€™s possible they have selected some in the past. After adoption from the shelter, TAPS relocates the animal to a spacious and swanky store located in a very popular and very expensive district in Burbank. Once there, the staff sets the dog up for re-adoption the and adds a hefty premium: weâ€™re taking around $700. For reference, the fee for the same neutered and microchipped dog at the shelter is around $95 or less.

Hereâ€™s why this is problematic. Although TAPS claims its methodology â€œfrees up shelter space,â€ it logically would have a minimal effect in achieving that end, given that the dogs they select are the most likely to be adopted, and fastest adopted at the shelter. Moreover, they are intercepting the animals from potential forever homes just for placement in a self-described halfway house. As a representative from TAPS has admitted in a comment to a previous review, they have even adopted animals who already had potential permanent adopters lined up! These methods perpetuate the problem it claims to be solving. So obviously â€œfreeing up spaceâ€ or finding forever homes is not their primary goal.

The inflated adoption fee doesnâ€™t seem to add up either. The shelter staff explained to me that the fee covers surgeries, microchipping, food, and lease payments for the Burbank boutique. Assuming the dogs are neutered/spayed and microchipped at the shelter and are eating moderately priced dog food, the vast majority of their adoption fee is going to their lease. The dogs there seemed healthy, and when I asked about the one dog who seemed to
need surgery, the staff insisted that the issue was cosmetic and would not be covered by the adoption fee. Note: my current dog had the same â€œcosmeticâ€ issue that later caused her recurring injuries and warranted surgery. Providing needed medical care doesnâ€™t seem to be the primary goal either.

So, that leaves us with one other remaining goal of TAPS, which is to provide an alternative for â€œpeople who find the shelter experience emotionally upsetting.â€ Okay so first of all I donâ€™t know a single person who fits that description. With the exception of those with PTSD, this is not an issue for most  people. If youâ€™re unwilling to rescue a dog because you find the shelter experience that unbearable, you probably shouldnâ€™t have a dog no less have a nonprofit dedicated to your â€œstruggle.â€ Second, if that is your main goal, get a less expensive boutique to house your adoptable animals so you can make the adoption fee accessible to more income levels and place more animals. You can still bring the dogs to popular areas with lots of foot traffic. The shelters do it all the time.

Finally, the most irksome issue with this place is how class (and race if you want to get deeper) are implicated in its mission. The organization, located in an affluent, mostly white part of LA, skims the shelters, located in the lower-income areas to take the best dogs away from low and middle income community members and potential forever homes so that they can be placed in a temporary shelter and adopted at an inaccessible fee by those with much greater means. Coupled with their aversion to the shelter experience, which perhaps requires a trek into a â€œdirtierâ€ and less white area, itâ€™s hard to not feel the subtle undertones of classism (and perhaps racism).

In short, donâ€™t feel good about yourself if you adopt here.</Review>

<response>{'time': 1522461801250, 'text': 'Katelyn, it may help you to have background on how Operation Adopt came into existence.  For years, The Animal Protectorates worked on "puppy mill" legislation to stop pet stores in Burbank, California from selling animals coming from commercial breeding facilities.  The alternative business model is to help rehome animals coming from shelters, humane societies or qualified rescue organizations in the same space.  Consumers visiting pet stores selling the commercially bred animals were spending thousands of dollars on purebred animals, having no idea where they were coming from.  We are really excited that these same consumers are finding joy in adopting orphaned animals coming from shelters.  Their mindsets are changing from thinking shelter animals are inferior to making a shelter animal a part of their family.  You are correct that adoption fees at Operation Adopt are higher than they are at a shelter.  This is because there are no subsidies from local agencies to offset the rent, staff salaries (we have to have staff to care for the animals), workers comp insurance, utilities, vet bills, and everything else that comes along with running a pet adoption center.  The perceived value of shelter animals are increasing in peoples minds (and hearts) because we are bringing them into a clean environment where meeting them is easy and supportive.  We also conduct home visits on every adoption to try to insure that these animals lives are headed in a better direction than where they came from (most of the animals we receive are neglected, some matted to the point of not being able to walk comfortably and many have medical issues requiring immediate and continuing vet care to get them to the point they are ready for adoption).  Sometimes though, even our rigorously vetted adopters have circumstances change in their lives that prevent them from keeping their pet.  Our guarantee is that in those circumstances we will receive their animal back and once again try to rehome the animal so that the animal will never enter the shelter again (our Purple Collar Promise to the animal).  So, our mission to that end has a positive impact on reducing the strain on shelters.\nWe hope knowing some more background will give you a different perception.  Thank you for visiting and for your compliment about the staff (we think they are pretty awesome too) and the good care we give the animals while they are with us.  We don\'t take your review as negative, on the contrary, we think all reviews are positive because they help us grow as the most unique adoption center in the country.'}<//response>< user_name>

She missed a high pitched squeal in the fill valves for our toilets. All of three fill valves needed to be replaced. The plumber actually told us that we should call the inspector and get our money back. Which is why I did. We have had a total of $800 worth of home warranty claims within the first month of owning our home. That isn't including the pool. They have given us a total of $50 after three weeks of sending them information about all of the things that were missed. She also stated in her report that she did not go on the roof. < Review>
We ordered the cheese pizza and mozzarella sticks. The pizza had a thin crust, which is just the way I like it. The slices are large, so you might be full after eating just one. We had the rest of the pizza for lunch the next day, and tasted good after re-heating. The meal was a good value.<//Review>

<Review>My family is truly happy we found this place after living here for 9 years...better late than never. The pizza has a delicious classic crust. The cheese is good quality unlike waxy cheeses elsewhere so if you love papa johns or dominoes, stay away.  The sauce is just right and also has classic taste. Toppings offered is probably the biggest plus. Huge selection! Nowhere else can you get potatoes which tastes absolutely amazing with sun dried tomatoes and garlic. They mince garlic just right that it melts away in your mouth. Delivery is always fast and at $0.99 delivery fee...how can you beat that?

Negative comments seem to be with those ordering or dealing with store via telephone. Iâ€™ve ordered online approx 6-7 times in 3 months and I havenâ€™t had an issue. Take a chance and try a few different variations and order at different times. I noticed sometimes late at night pizza is rushed so it may not be as well done (as in the bake) compared to ordering earlier but still no complaints here.

Keep up the great work!< /Review>< user_id>

<gmapID>0x808f8f68a0c0ac69:0x8abaa51eff9e3d4d< /gmapID>< time>
1558870007847</time>
< Text>
Double fried chicken is one of life's pleasures! :) Bonchon's KFC is crispy and moist, not heavily breaded and dry as a lot of fried chicken I've tried lately. And if you like spicy, the spicy is truly spicy, not overly so though, so don't be discouraged. I like to have both the spicy and soy garlic combination, so we can get the best of both worlds.

We've tried other food here as well, the seasoned fries (get it), the Japchae (meh), and the tacos (just okay). I would stick with the fries and the KFC.  The kimchi side is very small for the price so I wouldn't order it again. A Medium portion is good for two people if you want to take some leftovers home.

I've also pre-ordered here for a party and they had it ready for pick up at the appointed time. Parking in this lot can get tricky when during peak time but there's plenty of street parking on Hays St. We will definitely be back here.</Text>
< Rating>
4</Rating>

<text>I'm a fan of Korean fried chicken and saw this was close to the San Leandro BART station. I was very hungry, so when I saw the lunch specials I figured it wouldn't be enough. So I ordered a small combo with half soy garlic and half spicy. They warn you on the menu that your food might take time (30 mins) since it's usually cooked to order. I also ordered a banana milk (I thought it'd be home made but it's in a carton) and seasoned fries. The seasoned fries were seasoned perfectly and cooked well. When my chicken order came out, I was surprised at how large the pieces were. They're much larger than Kentucky Fried Chicken. I had to double check I ordered a small because it was enough to feed two people. Everything tasted great, including the side of daikon. I will definitely recommend this place to others who like Korean fried chicken.</text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMzZhlntEDTtNeuK4gWDNiXiCEU6Hqtsgjw7fyP=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO6dwwxec3stY0pN0BEwEOlhaXXq0GJ8EkTMvYg=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pics></record></dataset><record>

Great place for what it was!! Nice exhibits, various attractions (stingray bay, petting zoo, feed giraffes, etc) and food prices were reasonable at the cafe.  First time taking the kids; had a season pass for kids and I.  A lot bigger than what it looks like on the outside. We all enjoyed our time. We have yet to feed the giraffes and finish the African Adventure (which was pretty impressive). Will definitely be back!!<//Review>

< review>
Grab your Camera it's A great day at the zoo. All of the great animals a zoo should have but not the crazy crowds of the big city zoos. Feeding the giraffes are a quick fun thing all age kids and kid like adults can do. Make sure to see the bird show. You will be amazed how close they fly over the heads of the audience. Be sure to take the little ones to see the dinosaurs. Who doesn't wonder what it was like when  these animals roamed the earth.
Bring a picnic or eat just a few feet away from what looks like African tundra. Too many other areas to mention so get a pass and go as often as you like. You will see something new every time. Pro tip get the parking pass and use it here and at its fullest at the Shinzen Friendship Garden over and over again.</review>

John's Big Glo Ranch< /name>

<GmapID>0x8094673195546f4b:0xee80b918abd281d6</GmapID>< text>
Come see the baby rhinoceros! The Fresno Zoo has made a lot of improvements since I moved here over 20 years ago. When I first moved to Fresno I took my wife and kids to the Fresno Zoo. It was a traumatic experience. The animals were kept in horrendous conditions. We never went back. Today was our first time back. I was very impressed with the new exhibits that are much, much larger and more humane. I would go back again.</text>

<Rating>4<//Rating><review>Ample parking, do come prepared to pay $5 to access the park in which zoo is included. This is separate from the fee to access the zoo.
At the time of my visit there was much construction underway. I look forward to visiting the new exhibits when they are completed. I enjoyed the exhibits currently open, especially those I could walk through as with the birds. I loved that the exhibits are designed for the animals to roam or fly, with beautiful landscaping and ample water features.
I'm not a fan of children, so very glad I was able to purchase my ticket online for when the park opens at 9am and the hot, tired shrieking truly got started. Clean and strategically placed restrooms always a bonus.< /review><pictures>None</pictures><Resp>None</Resp><gmapID>0x8094673195546f4b:0xee80b918abd281d6< /gmapID></record>

<Text>I Came to the zoo with a 9 and11 year old. We were at the zoo for about three hours.  The kids were bored and all in our group disappointed.
The zoo could easily improve its customer satisfaction. We really had no idea how to explore the zoo. Here is an idea:  as soon as you enter the facility have a spot separated by fences for about 10 to15 separate zoo walks each exploring a different highlights of the zoo. The tour would start/finish at the same place. The finishing tour group would then line up for a different tour. In a period of two to three hours most of the zoo would have been seen.
These tours would be covered by the entrance fee. Donâ€™t charge another fee. You could let each tour leader accept tips.
As itâ€™s set up now, I will never return to your zoo.<//Text><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Resp>None< /Resp>< gmap_id>

This Zoo never fails to amuse our family. We get season passes every year and we go almost every week. It's such a great experience to get out of the city for a while and just be around amazing animals. Our kids love love the petting zoo. We figure it's cheaper to buy a zoo pass and have them enjoy this experience than try and get a pet. Lol but overall great place to visit<//review>

<rating>5< /rating>< Review>
Love all the new changes to the zoo and they haven't stopped. Working on an all new Asian area with hippo and more. It is so peaceful and relaxing there. Had a great dinner at Kopje Lodge where the rhinos seem to walk right up to you, really cool. The staff is for the most part friendly and willing to  answer any questions you have about the animals. Nice relaxing evening out. Not to pricey for members, I strongly recommend this because of all the discounts. ðŸ‘ðŸ‘ðŸ˜</Review>

<Rate>5< /Rate><pics>None<//pics>< review>
We've gotten family season passes to the Chaffee Zoo for 4 years straight. It's a great atmosphere and will always support our local zoo. Came here as a kid with my great grandma once a month or so and have fond memories here. Now I'm making memories with my 2 kids. 115 bucks for season pass and 35 or 40 for the zoorassic park season pass exhibit. It's worth it. We come once a week at least just to get the kids out and see some exotic animals. We've had our son's birthday here and been to another boys birthday and the staff are very accommodating. The food in the Africa area is also pretty good. Better then fast food but not quite restaurant style. Bird shows are always nice. I do wish they would open the path from the reptile house to the Sea Lions as that was open when I was a kid and since that area is a dead end there isn't alot of incentive to go over there.<//review>

< text>
We had a great day at the Fresno Zoo! It was our first time here so we booked an early time. It was a great idea because the park was not crowded at all and the animals seemed to be pretty active! The park design is nicely laid out, with restrooms and little spots to snack along the way. Feeding the giraffe and the sting rays were probably my favorite part! Make sure to buy the all inclusive passes they are the best way to get your money's worth. Make sure your phone is charged so you can scan your tickets if you buy them online. Great way to spend the day and inexpensive too!<//text>

<review>This is a wonderful zoo for the location and price but we have had a few frustrating issues.  The animal enclosures are all very large and do a good job of replicating the animal's natural habitats.  They are building a new section that looks very promising with some exciting new animals.  We especially enjoy the seal habitat, the African savanna area, and interactive areas like the stingray pool, petting zoo, and bird enclosures.  Some of the employees are a little too ambitious about enforcement of the mask rules considering everything is mostly outdoors.  The family membership is a good deal but we were disappointed with the dinosaur exhibit.  We paid the $36 to be able to get in all year only to have it cancelled after 2 months because they closed temporarily.  We emailed them about it but didn't not receive an extension or refund.< /review>< Gmap_id>

<username>Anthony Tang</username><Response>None</Response>< text>
We love bringing our little ones to this zoo. The giraffe feeding is the favorite stop for our family. Going to pet the farm animals isnâ€™t quite hitting the list yet at least.  We love stopping by to see the tiger, rhinos, and the elephants. There are a lot of animals to see and the enclosures are well kept. Not only that but the zoo keepers are highly knowledgeable.

The cafe at the zoo is great also with tasty and healthy options for kids and parents. The membership is well worth and has paid for itself many times over with the number of times we go a year. Not only that but the entrance line for members is always much shorter or nonexistent.

The Fresno zoo is a great place to spend time as a family.</text>

<date>1599424823638< /date><Rating>5</Rating><text>This zoo is so big, so you get a lot of exercise. Wear tennis shoes. So much interaction for the kids even Durning a pandemic! They have sanitizing stations everywhere and they have signs to remind you to wear masks. They take precautions to make sure people are six feet apart. Right now in the month of September through December they're going to have a dinosaur exhibition after those months it will be removed it really is cool and Worth to see there's even some dinosaurs that spray you with water. There is a food court you can relax and eat your food and there's a separate part to the food court where you could take your children and give them a bottle or help them nap or breastfeed your children. The bathroom seemed pretty clean it looks like they tend to them regularly. All the animals seem to be out and enjoying the warm weather they have misters for them or little waterfalls or some sort of water interaction so that they stay cool. You could feed the stingrays feed the giraffes for a couple of dollars per person. Right now you can not feed or pet the goats and sheep because of the covid 19. There is a play area that's currently closed for kids that is a water park the only thing available on it is the shower heads that you can use to cool down. The ice cream cones are only a dollar and they fill them up and put them also in a cup so it's basically like ice cream for two people for only $1. the sea lions are very active and I would suggest going underneath where the little cave area is so you can see them swimming underwater it's a great picture opportunity. They have little stands where you can pose for pictures everywhere! The family pass sis worth the money if you go frequently. If you love animals there's definitely lots to look at and they're very interactive. I personally had a nice experience with a macaw in the rainforest area if you say hello to him he will say hello back or if you dance and tell him to dance with you he'll dance back.<//text><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN_PmkaL9qqIhyk7D0DP0aJl8Z4KiWLgd85K1TW=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPQQuw-1sR9APpz76auLZw-9YemLTvMApZIpSeL=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPIWOIjZ_IBabxXbdOYhE0S4ch8Kv5HTT24Q8d9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMZqfNCmLR_2ZwZ9pqImeYgqPXAy8mXfBb1Og3S=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOAJFM9c0GpwOCNYDyVXp8pWAOb7DDicbB0kVF-=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP3WJe8wcBHVinjdc4lXD-pqLcDwtY5BRGOAvdS=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOWAgPTI0G5fVpgEv66ywEJY4UzXWMKfclFrFSa=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNskcNJXizN4Tq0tCSIBGO4LE7epHtIwvVw4JdA=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pics>< Resp>

<text>Flat out great zoo, and should be for a city this size.
The Sea Lion Cove is an award winning presentation.

And there is a awesome space to eat and watch the whole exhibit while the kids play on some rocks and the adults can relax! There is a really nice firepit too for when it's cold. And there are multiple stand up heaters to keep you warm too. Really nice job they are doing to the zoo!< /text><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMVTUwTyVhf9ZrKJAHamAILx0w7s_BVX_UcZ0D6=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOH1j3QlJWn9aKAxt6NL9juGpjT6zXVM4v3XYy2=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNOaiMqY4RHdirT4Dr3FwzEw9-MveeQPrmgBS6I=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNisXiVClyuBAOXF408m7FmjNMQVFCIuzK7lmkL=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOUQFOF-aR2lPFnJUAzMxEUad4C69uTMIJWtTZ4=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOY2_gJX82aGAxVuA81fKqIXpCQrlUizNCxYUSy=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM_LyXaDyp3mAdWlF8Db3UrAnq96KhLSs1pXsaT=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPd1XVg017P51Ju-i7Oai0tYeJqaDGPKa_KMAq4=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMEtFwI1KAu6F4qkNB-d-xRn6fqFeYpPnZwruHx=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN9_wtOUmxA0AxdpaENHGT8-SS90eCuP24854Ws=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPJuG993LUAI_hiib6EOi2IrqWE3UWTg0d4BFl9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMsRr0mj2ouLNlBbDymsH8t8mCpAk-CkihN0hCz=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN16FBaYW0fYhY78nt-ttyVUPADJmRlMagKBm8K=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPIxC4ZOiKPzslA5tcHzCZYBDuAX7AUQWLfg6GL=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics>< resp>

<review>Our family of 6 had a great day here while visiting from out of town. Good value. We did the total experience ticket so the Zoorasic Park, giraffe feeding, and stingray bay experiences were highlights. A few exhibits are closed for Covid and a fair amount of the zoo is under construction but we still had a great experience. The bird show was fun as well ... Not quite to the level I've seen at other zoos but still a great way to sit down for a while and be entertained.

Seems like they could have been doing elephant shows and sea lion shows. But hey, Covid puts a damper on things and is probably affecting all that.

I'd definitely recommend it for families to spend a day here. One of the highlights of our fresno visit.

I dropped $80 for lunch but the food was good and prepared on site. The wait for the food was a bit longer than expected and they didn't honor my no cheese request on my salad.<//review><time>1618102143446</time>< user_id>

< Review>
My kids & I absolutely LOVE the Chaffed Zoo, even tho it has a lot of exciting exhibits under construction at the moment, they still have plenty to see and do, feedings are still do able, the animal talks & shows, Zoorasic is till open YAY!, gift shop is setup right outside so it's nice. Strict COVID guild lines in place if you care to know that information. Also, I highly suggest getting the zoo's membership if you visit quite frequently, & of you don't I bet getting the membership will make you want to go more. Such a fun time for the family, even see just couples there as well. Great for everyone of all ages.</Review>

< Review>
My boys and I really enjoyed our animal adventure today. Just about every animal was out and about basking in the sun. It wasn't crowded and everyone for the most part wore masks. We really enjoyed feeding the giraffe. Because of social distancing we actually had a good amount of time to visit and ask questions. Everything was clean and the staff was polite and said hello all day. Great experience. We will be back soon.</Review>

<review>I spend a pleasant day wandering around the zoo. The bird aviaries were plenty large enough. All animal enclosure were large and clean. The animals all seemed content except for the tiger who was continually pacing. Probably close to feeding time. I would have liked to see more animals. The setup was a little confusing. I would recommend a few footprints painted on the sidewalk to guide visitors on a complete your of the grounds. I was pleased to see a giant anteater which you don't see often at zoos. I was also pleased to see the kangaroo exhibit. All staff that I talked to were very friendly and knowledgeable. <review>One of the best zoo I have been. It has a great collection of Africa animals, including at least 4 giraffes, 3 elephant, 3 rhinos (2 different kinds), 4 lions!!!! We went as a family trip when the zoo held it's annual Frogs & Fairytale activity. It had Disney princesses (besides Milan, Cinderella, or Rapunzel) for children to have pictures with, different art and craft activities, instant photo booth, and spot that professional helped our children to put up their make-up or face painting. We had a blast!!!!</review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNLOB2a_xiBQ0i-ntfM2IU9i8gEPxMRF5LjOyGM=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPhiMlcrs-jZeu48qDegdNiE9mwJLjAX1dZxJVK=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pictures>< Resp>

< userid>
102778388227958926933</userid>
<user_name>Shelby Cruz< /user_name>< Date>
1564929838169< /Date>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
A few years ago this zoo was not in the best shape and was no different than any other small town zoo. In recent years, however, they have made some excellent improvements to the facility including an expansion they call African Adventure. This area is awesome and houses many animals that call Africa their natural habitat like elephants, lions, cheetahs, rhinos and giraffes (that you can feed for just $3.00) but also some not so well known or favorites animals such as wildebeests and antelopes. The animals are fairly active for being in containment which is nice to see and the staff is always do friendly and never minds when my kids ask a million questions about the animals.  The food in this expansion is great but fairly pricey. I have a family season pass for 2 adults and 3 kids (we needed to add on a child as it normally comes with just 2) which costs about $75.00-$80.00 a year which is definitely worth it if you go more than 2 times a year. The pass gives you discounts throughout the zoo on food and souvenirs as well as a admission to some special events like their ice cream social and some events not open to the general public.<//Text>

<review>So many amazing opportunities for children of all ages to "dig" and unearth bones and truly gives them a hands on approach to possibilities.
Truly one must plan on more than a single visit as there are so many areas to visit.
The grounds are well maintained...plenty of clean restrooms. Parking is ample though at peak times, you may have to walk a bit further. There are food options as well as coffee bars for those must have cappuccinos and lattes.
The staff are all very helpful.< /review>< Gmap_id>

<user>118303779563742925665<//user><name>Rickita Morgan<//name><time>1584080831298</time><rate>3< /rate><review>So I recently decided to take my kids to the zoo. I thought it would be cool for them to see some of the animals that grace our TV screen with their own two eyes. I got to experience the SF zoo and I loved every minute of it. When we got there I instantly loved the realistic layout of every animal's enclosure. The zoo seemed well kept and the animals looked healthy and vibrant. That was until we got to the Tiger. First of all he was pacing back and forth obviously stressed but that I could have overlooked because it's common for some animals to become stressed in captivity. The thing that nipped and pulled at my heart strings was his frail extremely thin stature. He looked severely malnourished and it literally broke my heart to see him in such a state. It really bothered me to show my kids this Tiger (especially since he was one of animals they were looking forward to seeing). I never had a negative thought about animals in zoos but seeing him made it clear what PETA had been preaching all these years. Kind of ruined my perception of the zoo and I don't think I'll be going to the zoo anytime soon. Just my opinion.</review><Pics>None<//Pics><response>None</response><gmap_id>0x8094673195546f4b:0xee80b918abd281d6<//gmap_id></record>
</dataset><record>
< Review>
Really great zoo! Lots to see and do here. We spent about 5 hours here and STILL didn't see everything, but we were plenty satisfied with everything we did see and do. Besides general admission, you can pay a little extra for a giraffe feeding experience and to touch sting rays. Several animal trainer talks throughout the day at various locations.<//Review>

<Time>1556919516376</Time><gmap_id>0x8094673195546f4b:0xee80b918abd281d6< /gmap_id><rating>5< /rating>< text>
Petting the stingrays/sharks is by far my favorite part of the zoo, the stingrays are so friendly and cute. The food is decently priced for what you get, and the reusable cups are very nice and eco-friendly by not needing a straw! There are lids that are given to you for the cups when you pay for your food, and thereâ€™s a spot for you to drink out of and it does not leak. The petting zoo is always lots of fun and the zookeepers in there are always very informative and friendly when you ask them questions about the animals. The sea lion and seal show is also very cute! The sea lions are adorable and so is the seal, and itâ€™s very informative, teaching kids lots about the pinnipeds they have at the zoo! 10/10 recommend<//text>

< Text>
So much to see now that they've been updating and building new areas. The new water play area is a nice place to cool off but to my 5 year old it makes the zoo more about playing in the water rather than about the animals. But a great addition for those with annual memberships looking for a way to cool off in the summer months.</Text>

<Review>It is not easy to keep animals in a zoo and still have a natural feel to the show. Fresno Chaffee Zoo does exceedingly well.
Looking at the elephant shaking a palm tree by the water side reminded me of a real wild scene just a couple of miles down from Murchison Falls, Uganda.
Some animals on the resident list were not there, but staff explained the situation.
Great place for a day out!< /Review>< Resp>

<Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
I have seen many zoos in California and Chaffee is still my favorite. The layout is beautiful, there are a wide variety of animals to observe and the food is delicious. There is seating throughout the park. The zoo also offers a variety of kids activities throughout the year. I highly recommend purchasing a membership, especially if you are a Fresno resident. The membership will also get you discounts at other zoos.< /Review>

<Review>I took my son on a day trip to Fresno yesterday to the Zoo, mall, dinner and movie...Wow they have done so much with this zoo, we loved it super relaxed not crowded beautiful animals and the absolute stars are their zookeepers!! So personal they talk to you and answer any and all questions you have and are the sweetest people.  One also told me they have special areas for kids and adults with special needs and like my son he is autistic with many sensory issues...i am definitely going to try a trip with him next time.  anyway for the kids to calm down after a meltdown or whatever may be bothering them.  What a plus in my book!! The cafe they have there we ate at is right on the African Adventure very yummy food above what i would expect.  You also can sit right there outside and watch the elephants, rhinos, giraffe etc. while you eat such fun!! The animals are superbly taken care of as well...We truly enjoyed our time there and will most definitely be returning and recommending to friends and family.< /Review><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNbbl_Qr337yhcSW_-48XdIae5-3DnI_O3otfH5=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN16a0pVS6Pt0T-QosxbzEZQ-PuVvYqFyWqGCgR=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNGDLN2NhDp6WV-Xq4FT4CBPwZwm6ZIyc4UcIjW=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNnBCNHcuyJe1Pd0cyJwF43f3Rw2tBYfxWpEM4b=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNrkS0dt8kNN4JcaLh5AvzIFW-ZPDk32-BjE5YD=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipObB553_I_644mgnrC_8VFZSwc5vHzv7A7V2q7D=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO_3Z1kAYYMwAZRs2vGpmaeoqYqvY2f1EaC0LuH=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipORYpzNWkqdiWvpuOT9vLyXWBod-VQ04iWEGQ8q=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipORX40IQHi6ku54tevuCw8gPS9kW8wHoo_reBUV=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMB7Qrb1oYxA6LP0sGhRFHIb--ku0n1fylOrxtN=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNFZ691qOTUUK8NHFb8kPmCJX7NRauWTdY0mOvi=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP4vfBAJeQbR60jZiJzrhtQYSnSSr0dJ_dBw0WF=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPBzfoizkIC05yZ1VOAFHU2HcxuKYJFtOmY7N24=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics>< rating>

< resp>
None<//resp>
< Review>
Beautiful and well maintained zoo. Lots of space between exhibits to space yourself away from other families. Several outdoor dinning options, hand sanitizer station easliy available and clean restrooms.   The staff was very friendly and helpful for the most part. We did have a very negative experience at the giraffe feeding. The giraffes themselves where awsome. You can get up close to see them. Where it went wrong was the very rude and unhelpful paid staff. They clearly need more training in customer service. It was not organized and no signs to where you should stand or park your stroller. The hand sanitation was placed after the lettuce pick up area so you had to walk to that point then go back to pick up the lettuce. The staff was barking out orders. A few signs and proper placement of items would have made it easier on everyone. At one point we were the only ones in the pavilion so it was not like the staff had a lot to do. It just needs to be better organized so you know what to do. Otherwise the feeding of the giraffes was interesting. The volunteer staff was great. They specifically explained what we should do and told us about the animals.  Overall the zoo was really fun and a great place to spend the day.<//Review>

There was a lot of construction going on that will likely not end any time soon & because of Covid you have to walk down a preset path. The Reptile exhibit is closed and a lot of the animals have been "relocated" to another exhibit that they're working on. Unfortunately those exhibits are all closed so we didn't get to see about a third of the animals.
Overall, it was still a fun experience and the lack of people made for a more enjoyable experience.</Text>

< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>
< Review>
My family loves the local zoo. It's not as big as sa San Diego Wild Animal park, but you can feed the giraffes and stingrays! It's usually not overly crowded  and its completely possible to see the entire pack, shows included, in a single day. My favorite time of year to go is actually December.  They have an event called Zoolights. The entire park is decked out in Christmas lights, Santa Claus is available for secret sharing and picture taking and there is even FREE hot chocolate handed out during the event! Dont forget to stop by their food shack for some of the best soft pretzels around.  All and all, we love Fresno Chaffee Zoo!</Review>

< review>
Really great place to go for a nice day out with the kids or on a date with your partner. The staff is really friendly and the animals look well taken care of. Make sure to bring sunscreen and lots of water on your visit. The new safari exhibit is really great. Although it can't compete with the San Diego Zoo and Safari park, the Chaffee Zoo is something great that everyone in Fresno should visit every once in a while.</review>

A bit disappointing but didnt expect much otherwise. Pretty much you can only visit outdoor sections due to covid. shame that they make you pay extra for some exhibits, its not that big of a zoo in the first place. the elephant giraffe rhino areas were nice. otherwise wasn't anything overly exciting. The sea lion area seems like a huge section what a waste of space for the 1-2 sea lions hiding swimming in the corner. There was very little or unclear signage of where to go and what to do anywhere in the zoo and they dont even hand you a map when you walk in.<//Review>

Through Measure Z, the Chaffee Zoo has been able to improve and expand the zoo to make it a quality experience. The new Africa exhibit is really nicely done and the Kopje Lodge has decent food for moderate prices. If you live in the area and have kids or just like having somewhere to go wander I would suggest getting a year pass, it pays for itself in 7 trips. Great place to go for dates without spending a ton of money. Pro tip: If you want to go when it is less crowded, go in to morning. The animals are also more active. During the summer, always go as soon as it opens, before it gets hot.<//Review><rating>5</rating>< gmap_id>

<text>Nice little zoo. Lots to see. The animals look well cared for. There are staff/zookeeper talks throughout the zoo where you can witness feedings, learn about them and ask questions. We enjoyed experiencing touching the sting rays and sharks as well as feeding the giraffes. Loved the elephant enclosure, which is mixed with other animals like zebras and rhinos where they have a large area to roam. There's also a splash pad for the kids because it's hot in California!< /text>< pictures>

< Text>
It was a pretty warm day in the valley today, but that didn't stop us from visiting the zoo. The only exhibit that was closed was the Reptile House, which I wasn't too sad about (lol don't like snakes). It was exceptionally clean, the staff was super nice and friendly. There were possibly 2 habitats that didn't have animals (sick/injured animal I believe or just being moved). It always brings back memories coming here and I'm glad we came today to support the zoo and see all the wonderful exhibits and animals. Oh and the African Zoofari is AMAZING. Oh and for $3 you can even feed the giraffes ðŸ¦’ ðŸ˜Š.</Text>

< Text>
A very nice sized zoo to spend the afternoon or even a few hours. Key areas to make sure to visit are the sea lion habitat, ray petting area, feed the giraffes, and walk through the large reptile house. Parking can fill up quickly, so arriving closer to opening may make that easier. Lots of feedings throughout the day along with the shows with different animals make this a recommended zoo to visit.</Text>

It is the fastest-growing zoo in the nation and it has some marine animals like seals and stingrays you can touch, it has an amazing open space for African safari that resembles the San Diego Safari Landscaping where animals roam freely around a beautiful Lake. We fed the giraffes and got to learn so much from zookeepers! We definitely will be back many more times, got the membership which provides a lot of benefits like 10% discounts in the cafe and gift shop and preview events. having been to huge zoos like San Diego Zoo and San Diego Safari in the Los Angeles Zoo, we were surprised beyond our expectation at this beautiful and well-kept Zoo. It has so much to Explore! Oh, before I forget. My kids also spent a good hour digging in the dino dig, it was actually really fun to unearth bone and to get a real feeling of what it would be like being part of it fossil Expedition team.<//text></record>

<user>116321601132576957822<//user><Review>Love, love love Fresno Chaffee Zoo. This oasis just off 99 and Olive (or Belmont) is a real joy to see - repeatedly. As Fresno has grown, the zoo has grown in size, quality, and aesthetics. It's a landmark worthy of being proud of our city. While it is not what I would call inexpensive, it IS a great value for your dollar and should be considered a special biannual or quarterly special treat for the kids (and you). Both exciting AND exhausting, plan for lunch (and rest) at the Kopje Lodge (great food choices), the Safari Cafe, or bring your own picnic. To see the whole zoo requires a LOT of walking so try to plan your visit where you land at food/rest at appropriate times. Highly recommend.</Review><name>Bryan LeGare< /name><gmap_id>0x8094673195546f4b:0xee80b918abd281d6<//gmap_id><Response>None<//Response></record>

< Text>
While the entrance is not fancy you quickly find out it drops you directly into the action. I beautiful walk through tropical bird environment that thrills children and adults alike. Moving on to the elephants you are sill thinking this is a standard zoo adventure until you come out on the Savanna. 40 acres of beautiful environment designed so well you don't notice the barriers between the hunters and the prey. Off in the distance a herd of elephants sways while different antelope types wander and occasionally bound through. A pride of lions sits to one side. Lounging on rocks and lording it over all, cubs playing and lionesses watching over them. A rhinoceros wanders through with her baby at her side. Amazing everyone. Next is on to the giant enclosed tropical rain forest complete with waterfall and fowl of all types. The zoo in Fresno is well worth the visit. If you in town at loose ends or looking for something on the weekend to do with yourself or the family. You can't lose with this one.</Text>

<text>Came here with my family on an off day. It was an awesome trip to this zoo! They have a good variety of animals and reptiles. Animals look well taken care of. Admission, parking, and even food are of reasonable cost. My toddler son really enjoyed seeing reptiles, orangutans, elephants, and rhinos. He also had a blast in the Dino Dig area. Was a great experience and will come back. Some friends say it's the best zoo around(better than Oakland and SF).

As for the negatives reviews below.
1. Prices. This place is NOT that expensive ðŸ˜‚. Money goes to caring for the animals and employees. If PRICES are an issue then go park or stay home
2. Animals. Many of these animals are endangered or wouldn't last in the wild. They are well taken care of and in a clean environment.
3. Parking. Parking DOES stink!! I agree on that but arrive early then.</text>< response>

< Text>
I have gone to the Fresno Chaffee Zoo since I started college in the early seventies and seen how it has grown and improved into one of the best Zoos to visit. Our family has been members since my children were born and now it is a favorite family event with my grandchildren.  When I was young, the San Diego Zoo was a frequent event so I grew up loving the experience. The Fresno Chaffee Zoo is easier to experience in a day and an extremely memorable experience with special events and exhibits throughout the year. It's well worth visiting.

Visiting Zoos elsewhere in the Nation is something we have done over the years so I have seen some wonderful ones elsewhere, like Atlanta, Georgia and Portland. Each one has unique things and this Zoo does as well.<//Text>

Enjoy going with my family,  safari is the best.</Text>
< time>
1599366692148< /time>
</record></dataset><record>
< Text>
July the 3rd, Friday, 2020....as the morning sun rose in the east, the Fresno Chaffee Zoo was ready for the visitors of the day.  Even though the Covid-19 cloud hung over Fresno County, the zoo was well prepared for this problem.  The animals didn't seem to mind that the people observing them had on masks and werepracticing social distancing.  They were content with their food and well maintained enclosures.  For the observing humans, there were plenty of hand sanitizer stations found across the grounds of the zoo. Granted the zoo had to close a few of the enclosed exhibits because of the "19" mandates, but the personal of the zoo had great presence and we think there were smiles beneath their masks.  Questions were always answered, and often you came away with more information then your question was asked about.  The zoo has come a long way since this person visited it when Nosey was still in her enclosure. So if you have not seen the Chaffee Zoo in 10 years or more, take some time out of your schedule, and if necessary,  put on a mask and stroll through a wonderful zoo. Hopefully in a few months the mask will not be necessary.  Enjoy...< /Text>

< Text>
Amazing zoo! Almost every habitat had a very knowledgeable intern available to answer any questions. The exhibits allow for great movement and guest visibility of the animals. The number of bathrooms and water fountains are amazing. You are never more than a short walk from either item. Most importantly is the cost. The admission cost is very low. The mac and cheese was the highlight of lunch though. Amazing!<//Text>

I've been all over the country and this is one of the best zoos I've ever been to. The park is clean, the animals are happy and cared for, and there are always helpful employees and volunteers nearby. <user_name>Liz Bushman Tokarczuk<//user_name>< resp>

< Date>
1536379884519<//Date>
< rate>
5<//rate>
<gmapID>0x8094673195546f4b:0xee80b918abd281d6< /gmapID>< text>
This is an amazing zoo. I, like many others, grew up when it was slightly shabby and perpetually struggling until the early 2000s; now, it is THE jewel of the Central Valley. With exhibits in both Spanish and English, a cheap entry fare, and an intimate setting coupled with the gorgeous Safari half, the Chaffee Zoo is absolutely the star of any casual tour of Fresno.

If you are a resident, purchase the yearly membership -- it more than pays for itself if you visit more than twice a year. The community and heart behind it is bigger than any nationally-recognized zoo.</text>

< user_id>
115049955966582509655< /user_id>
<name>rosa armstrong<//name><time>1501308365656<//time>< rate>
5< /rate>
< review>
Visited this zoo this year with my kids. We Loved it! We went on a Saturday and it did get busy but we still had a good time. It does get less packed during the weekday. The paths are smooth for strollers, restrooms were clean, the park was clean. No graffiti or trash laying around. A lot of educational areas and the Safari area is really cool! There's a restaurant right by it so you can eat and see the animals. My kids loved it. Petting the stingrays is a must! It's really cool and feeding the giraffes too! Will be returning!</review>

< Text>
I have many fond memories of visiting the zoo with family and my school. I remember when you could ride the camels and take a picture, my mom still has the photo.

Now that I'm older and have my own children I visited this weekend and am so happy to see the constant improvements and new exhibits. The cafe is gorgeous. The water playground is a gem when you get tired of walking around in the heat with a cranky toddler. I especially love the little tables and chairs in corners of the zoo to sit down and eat snacks I brought with us. I nursed my baby there comfortably and then when we continued our tour I was delighted to see they actually have a breastfeeding nook in the kids area by the food shack.

Sea lion cove is another favorite and to be able to see them swimming underwater was an awesome experience. Thank you Chaffee zoo and staff. Your hard work and dedication is appreciated by many families.</Text>

<user>106682400452257654722<//user>< username>
ToddnAmber Newsome</username>
<Date>1525992267031< /Date>< rate>
5< /rate>
< review>
This zoo is wonderful. The price is very reasonable ($12 per adult, children's prices vary by age but are less). The zoo is landscaped beautifully, they take good care of the animals (which means you may not see certain animals if it's too hot outside), and the food near the African exhibit if very good (but pricey). Costs $5 to park for the day (but gives you access to the surrounding park). Bring $3 to feed the Giraffes! Petting zoo and wonderful reptile house also available. Bathrooms clean and well stocked. Family bathrooms also available.</review>

Matthew Monnier<//Name>

1459968307345<//time>
<Rate>5</Rate><Review>My wife, kids, and I came to Fresno for a wedding from Florida and decide to go to the zoo with our infant and 4 yr old. We must say that this was a Great zoo! Especially for the price! You get the chance to get up close and personal with so many animals like elephants, rhinos, gazelle, sloths, monkeys, a bunch of different species of birds, stingrays and sharks. There was also a great petting zoo area that you are able to interact and pet goats, baby cows, donkeys, turkeys, and lamas which my son and I enjoyed a lot! Plus We were amazed that our 4 yr old son was able to feed a giraffe in the new African animals exhibit (which is massive) for only $2. He was Sooo excited by the experience that he fed them 10 more times! The food and drink prices were very reasonable as well.  Plus they are military and senior citizen friendly and offer a discounted rate for both.  It was a great way for the whole family to hang out and not spend a lot of money. If we ever come back to the Fresno area we are definitely coming back to this zoo. We highly recommend it anyone!!!<//Review>< Pictures>

<review>Being a Member, I don't ever have wait long. Show my pass, scan in, and adventure begins with my little crew.

We always eat at the Safari area. As a member, I get a discounts so I enjoy it. I don't wait too long for my food and portion is good size. Kids love the Mac N Cheese and I definitely love the portion of that. My most recent visit was about a month ago. I ordered extra fries like usual and this time I felt I got very little for the price I was paying.  Normally the fries would be enough for 3 kids, however on that day, it only was enough for 2 kids out of the 5. I didn't say anything at the time since I gave my meal to the kids because they were hungry.

For that particular day, I give the trip to the Zoo a 3 star rather than a 4 star.</review>< Date>

< name>

<review>I drive the two hours from Stockton to come to this zoo instead of any of the several that are closer to us because it's amazing!

They have the Stingray bay where unlike other places, you can actually feed them! It's 1 dollar for a cup of little fish and they come right up to you and eat from your hand!
You can also feed the giraffes which seems to what the younger kids really enjoy.
I haven't been through it but they have the Kanga walk as well.

My personal fave is the big cats which there is no shortage of. They have tons of room to run around and do lion, and tiger stuff!

Overall it's a really cool place and worth the visit for sure.<//review><time>1547250374760<//time>< gmapID>

<Pics>None<//Pics><Gmap_id>0x8094673195546f4b:0xee80b918abd281d6< /Gmap_id><Review>I do love this zoo and am a member. Having visited zoos all over California, I can say there are some that I just find down right depressing. This is NOT one of them.
The chaffee zoo is both part of the conservation and repopulation programs, so you will often see babies at this zoo. They staff is amazing and willing to answer any question your overly exuberant child might ask. The zoo is also working hard to continually improve the animal habits, making them appear and feel more like natural habitats.
The African safari habitat is amazing and one of my favorite parts of the zoo.

Be prepared for the $5 parking fee. Buy your tickets online so you can skip the line at the gate. It will cost you $3 to feed the giraffes, and $2 to visit the stingrays and a dollar more feed them. The current dinosaur exhibition has an additional entrance fee.<//Review><time>1562539987469< /time></record></dataset><record>

< review>
Great place to walk aerpijd and enjoy the different exhibits.   The price is reasonable and the sights are many.  Highly recommend good walking shoes.   Great number of chairs and benches to take a seat. Lots if things to do for the little ones.  Recommend clearing your calendar for the day and getting an early start to avoid the parking issues. Easy to find off the freeway and the staff are phenomenal.   Truly professional knowledgeable and courteous.   Thank you Fresno Zoo!< /review>

<user>103177100800831824735<//user>< Name>
Daniel Silva< /Name>
<Date>1400136360686<//Date><rating>5</rating>< Text>
I love this park. This park holds many great memories to me; from swinging on the swings as a child to feeding the ducks and geese with my fiance.

My favorite section of the park is of course the geese and ducks. They are so cheerful and happy to see people all the time. They just want to be fed and full so they can sleep comfortable in there giant pond.

Being there is just relaxing overall. The green grass makes it peaceful, the trees make the place shady, and the overall setting is just great for families and close ones alike.

You can take meat over to the park and sit on the benches, barbequing all day. Take the family out for an escape away from home or just chill out on the grass with whoever you want. You're only limited to your imagination.

There's also bathrooms there, so it's an all day type of place, and there is also a zoo inside Roeding park.

The zoo holds many animals like lions, elephants, alligators, snakes, tortoise, and much more. It's just a place you have to go to enjoy and see it for yourself.<//Text>

< review>
The zoo is a very nice zoo. There is a great range of animals, its laid out well, and the kids seemed to love it. We greatly enjoyed it!

Our only issue during the day was the customer service, or rather lack of, from the cafe to the shop, the stingray people to the front gate. Every person we spoke to was either rude, condescending, bored or a combination thereof. It left a sour note, especially when my 8 year old nephew asked for help in the shop with a product and was ignored by 2 staff members. I would think a place that deals with people on the regular would be more personable.</review>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
It's kind of like a maze. I somehow missed out on quite a few attractions, but all-in-all it was beautiful. There are a lot of birds. The sea lions seem happy. The orangutans seemed bored. The reptile exhibit had a large variety and I really enjoyed the sting ray and shark exhibit. Feed the sting rays and sharks. They suck the fish and shrimp out of your hands. Don't be scared. I was scared and I'm glad I fed them. The sharks feel like rocks when you touch them.</text>

<userid>103040935674899612429</userid><username>Mary Bagorio</username><time>1528956574960</time>< Rate>
4</Rate>
< review>
Roeding Park Dog Park is divided into two sections, one for small dogs (less than thirty pounds) and one for larger dogs. There was water available for your dog and "poop bags". Apparently people used the bags because there was not an accumulation of dog feces, the grass area was kept clean. Only two other visitors while we were there. We spent approx. 2 hours. The small dog area had 1 picnic table in a shaded area for the people to sit and one cement bench in the sun. Big dog area had a picnic table in the sun, and no shade anywhere. Guess the weather would be the deciding factor, too hot to sit in the sun. Otherwise quiet, friendly and a nice experience.<//review>

<name>Shey Harlacher<//name><Review>Take the kiddos here once a week and always come with put of town guests. This is a FABULOUS zoo. All of the animals are rescues, woukd not survive in the wild or are part of a species rehabilitation program. Fantastic exhibits and reasonably priced, delicious food. So many learning experiences and activities for kids. They have sandboxes, fossil digs, sting ray touch exhibit. My daughter loves the safari jeep at the lion exhibit. Admission is very reasonable compared to other zoos. Its very clean and the staff is knowledgeable. Plus you can also buy a parking pass for the Fresno regional parks at their box office to save you a trip downtown.</Review>< gmapID>

<Date>1526350973837<//Date>< rate>

<Review>I've been going to the Chaffee Zoo since i was in kindergarten. I love the Chaffee Zoo.
As an adult i purchased the membership for me and 2 adults with 2 children for $110. That's 365 days I'm allowed to go for FREE.
Within a week i made back what i spent here comes with a 10% discount as well.  This zoo has become apart of my life.  With the awesome water feature my daughter and i will coming here over the summer.  They have alot of events planned through out the year.
Please visit there website for more information</Review>< Pictures>

<Text>My family absolutely loves this zoo! We have been members for two years. They have something for every age group. You can pet the sharks and sting rays at Sting Ray Bay. Feed the giraffes in the new Safari area,  which is really AWESOME!! Cool down, and play in the water by the bone dig area. Watch a really neat bird show. Or sit for literally hours while your kids run from one side of the glass wall to the other, watching the sea lions play! They have multiple options for food. They have the traditional snack bar area that serves hot dogs, nachos,  corndogs , and drinks.  Or what we like to do is go to the Safari area.  They have this HUGE sitting area outside under a covered patio over looking the animals.  The have multiple little restaurants to choose from. (kind of cafeteria style) They have Italian food, deli style up scale sandwiches,  beef and chicken  burgers, chicken strips, sliders and more. Everything is made fresh while you wait right in front of you. If you are a member you will get discounts on everything ðŸ˜‰ I also recommend buying a few( depending upon how large your family is) of the novelty cups. The refills on them are only about a dollar and change. You can bring them w/ you each time you return to the zoo. It saves a lot of money. Also the food portions are quite large.  You could definitely get away with sharing your meals. Restrooms are always clean. Parking is only 5 bucks. I recommend coming early. I believe it opens at 8am. It's such a wonderful place to visit.  They animals are clearly will taken care of.  This zoo has inspired my daughter to be come a zoologist. The love for the animals really comes through when you speak to any of the zoo crew.</Text><gmapID>0x8094673195546f4b:0xee80b918abd281d6<//gmapID><Date>1534456017693<//Date>< username>

<rating>3</rating>< review>
The enterance and the first exibits I visited were beautiful, leading to the only problem I seen, the Giraffe feeding. We are allowed to feed the giraffes, but not allowed to touch them. This doesn't seem like a too big of a problem, until you have many children in the feeding area being yelled at from staff not to touch them Every time they hold their hand out. If giraffes are so dangerous that they can break your hand in one hit with their head, why couldn't they have us pay to feed another less dangerous animal. Staff should not have to yell at children to not touch the giraffes from across the exibit. The feeding area should be closed and the giraffes should only be looked at from a view like all the other animals.<//review>

<review>When I traveled to Fresno and was lucky enough to have a little time the afternoon before I left, I thought visiting the zoo would be a nice way to kill some time. I completely underestimated this zoo. It was fantastic! The African exhibit was incredible and I could have spent the entire day watching the animals interact on the Savannah. The monkey cage was also ablot of fun. They had stingrays that you could pay to interact with that looked fun, but I didn't a chance to participate. My only complaint was the sea lion habitat. Very nice zoo, parking will get pretty crazy on weekends and you have to pay to park before you even step foot to pay to enter the zoo. But they have numerous animals that you would find at any other zoo. The staff here are great, and very knowledge about each animal they have. The cafe is in the heart of the zoo and it was also really good. Maybe we were just starving lol.. They have nachos, hotdogs, churros, grilled sandwiches, chicken salads, burgers.. Also a good selection of desserts like cookies, brownies, pie, etc..<//text>

< name>
John Murdock< /name>
<Date>1556980935326</Date><rating>5</rating><resp>None</resp><Text>I want to give a shout out to Fresno Chaffee Zoo.
Growing up with Chaffee Zoo and Roeding Park filled my mind with many exciting memories as a child that has helped shaped my character, personality, and well being, with adventure treks and escapades of a little ones imagination to the profound respect for animals, being an animal lover myself.
I witnessed all the amazing upgrades and transformation of Chaffee Zoo and all for the better of the animals and entertainment.
Yes there were dark days of yesterday's past with the famous Nosey the elephant who spent many of her years in a tight closed-in metal bar space. As a child it was so exciting at that time to be able to feed her peanuts. I will not forget the touch of her trunk, she loved people. I profoundly remember a donation bin to upgrade Noseys environment, one which you drop your coin as it spirals down in a circling cyclone. Thank God Fresno residents came through along with many others in thier contributions, I believe it was in 1982 Nosey had a new upgraded and amazing home now of natural dirt, a swimming pool, waterfall, and toys to play with. She also for the first time in over 30 years had other elephant companions. I'm glad she had this experience before her passing. I believe to this day it was Nosey who inspired many to fight for the animals here to have much more. Yes there's the bitter/sweet of animals being in captivity but today most of these animals were born more or less in captivity and wouldn't survive the wild. So enjoy the many adventures to come. Thank you all who had part in giving Nosey her new home and for the amazing upgrades of the Fresno Chaffee Zoo.
As an adult I walk into the zoo with my annual membership and my children at my side seeing the excitement of sparkle in eye. It these moments that I re-live the child in me. Let the journey begin!<//Text>< user>

<user_name>Mr F</user_name><review>As zoos go I'll as far as to say it's a C+. To start, at it's busiest parking is impossible. The lot arrangement is poor due to it's single entry/exit point, lack of room, and the fact that it is shared by the amusement park across the street. Parking was $5 but I could see it being free when it's not so busy.

The membership to the zoo for a whole family is $99, if you can't decide if you want to buy it in line you can actually pay your normal entry fees and then comeback and have that day's fees go toward the  membership if you do decide to get one. There are, of course, different levels to membership but the gist is you can stroll in on the member line and get 10% off purchases in the zoo.

The zoo itself does have some great exhibits, most of what you'd expect to find at a zoo but some are just a bit lacking. I've only been here a few times so there may be other ways around but from what I can tell there are at least two, maybe more, exhibits that so not have handicap/stroller ramps on one or both sides.

The dining facilities range from a medium sized quick bite spot to a large shaded, artesianal foods with an amazing view of the zoo's largest exhibit containing many African favorites cohabitating in one area. There aren't many food stands or generally opportunities for snacks besides these two spots and the gift shop - wouldnt want to tempt people to feed the animals I guess...I still wish they had Dippin' Dots..

Animals seem well taken care of and there are certainly a variety to be seen. If I could change one exhibit, I'd give the Tiger much more space. Seems a shame but you be the judge.

This zoo is well kept and popular with locals but it really doesn't have that something to it that I would needed to want to keep coming back. It's not bad by any means, just average I think.< /review><resp>None</resp><gmap_id>0x8094673195546f4b:0xee80b918abd281d6<//gmap_id>< rating>
3</rating>

Today was our fourth visit and it was incredible. The staff was very friendly and volunteered information all day. And it wasn't just a few employees that went out of their way. <Gmap_id>0x8094673195546f4b:0xee80b918abd281d6< /Gmap_id>< Name>
Mr F< /Name>
<review>As zoos go I'll as far as to say it's a C+. To start, at it's busiest parking is impossible. The lot arrangement is poor due to it's single entry/exit point, lack of room, and the fact that it is shared by the amusement park across the street. Parking was $5 but I could see it being free when it's not so busy.

The membership to the zoo for a whole family is $99, if you can't decide if you want to buy it in line you can actually pay your normal entry fees and then comeback and have that day's fees go toward the  membership if you do decide to get one. There are, of course, different levels to membership but the gist is you can stroll in on the member line and get 10% off purchases in the zoo.

The zoo itself does have some great exhibits, most of what you'd expect to find at a zoo but some are just a bit lacking. I've only been here a few times so there may be other ways around but from what I can tell there are at least two, maybe more, exhibits that so not have handicap/stroller ramps on one or both sides.

The dining facilities range from a medium sized quick bite spot to a large shaded, artesianal foods with an amazing view of the zoo's largest exhibit containing many African favorites cohabitating in one area. There aren't many food stands or generally opportunities for snacks besides these two spots and the gift shop - wouldnt want to tempt people to feed the animals I guess...I still wish they had Dippin' Dots..

Animals seem well taken care of and there are certainly a variety to be seen. If I could change one exhibit, I'd give the Tiger much more space. Seems a shame but you be the judge.

This zoo is well kept and popular with locals but it really doesn't have that something to it that I would needed to want to keep coming back. It's not bad by any means, just average I think.< /review>< Date>
1558881714265</Date>

<gmapID>0x8094673195546f4b:0xee80b918abd281d6<//gmapID></record></dataset><record>
< text>
This is a great zoo. Recently enrolled my kids in zoo camp (2 hours of driving each day for a week). The photo I took with my kids is one I used on a book cover and had enlarged to put up on my wall.

I've visited often with and without the kids. Regular times and special events - ice cream, behind the scenes, Dia de la Familia, Zoo Boo, Zoo Lights, and Safari Night (adults only).

The zoo keepers are friendly and knowledgeable, care about the animals and give the administration ideas about constantly improving and updating the zoo.

On hot days there is now a kids water play area, and we always visit the reptile house (probably the most comfortable spot in the zoo).

Also recommend venturing up to the African Safari area. Not only is it well done but that's where you'll find the best food in the zoo. Woodfired pizza is our favorite. Then see the cheetahs up close (glass wall). Closer than any other zoo I've visited.

Too many great exhibits and experiences to list. Well worth the visit and certainly an amazing value for a family!</text>
